<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="75" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75">
<taxonomicName authorityName="B. D. Sun, A. J. Chen, Houbraken &amp; Samson" authorityYear="2020" class="Eurotiomycetes" family="Aspergillaceae" genus="Talaromyces" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Talaromyces albisclerotius" order="Eurotiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="75" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="albisclerotius">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="75">Talaromyces albisclerotius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
produces white sclerotia on OA, grows restrictedly on CYA, YES, DG18 and OA and does not grow on CYAS.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="75" type="in">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75">In.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75">
<taxonomicName class="Eurotiomycetes" family="Aspergillaceae" genus="Talaromyces" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Talaromyces" order="Eurotiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="75" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="section" section="Trachyspermi">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="75">Talaromyces section Trachyspermi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="75" type="colony diam, 7 d (mm)">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75">Colony diam, 7 d (mm).</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75">CYA 5-8; CYA 30 °C 3-4; CYA 37 °C No growth; MEA 19-20; MEA 30 °C 8-9; OA 13-14; YES 6-7; CREA No growth; CYAS No growth; DG18 5-6.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="75" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75">Colony characters.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75">
CYA 25 °C, 7 d: Colonies moderately deep, slight sulcate; margins entire; mycelium white; texture floccose; sporulation dense; conidia 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="75">en masse</emphasis>
greyish yellow-green (68); soluble pigments absent; exudates absent; reverse buff (45). MEA 25 °C, 7 d: Colonies moderately deep, sulcate; margins entire; mycelium white and primrose (66); texture floccose; sporulation dense; conidia 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="75">en masse</emphasis>
pistachio green (92); soluble pigments absent; exudates absent; reverse ochreous (44). YES 25 °C, 7 d: Colonies moderately deep, plane; margins entire; mycelium white; texture floccose; sporulation moderately dense; conidia 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="75">en masse</emphasis>
pistachio green (92); soluble pigments absent; exudates absent; reverse buff (45). DG18 25 °C, 7 d: Colonies moderately deep, plane; margins entire; mycelium sulphur yellow (15); texture floccose; sporulation sparse; conidia 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="75">en masse</emphasis>
greyish yellow-green (68); soluble pigments absent; exudates absent; reverse sulphur yellow (15). OA 25 °C, 7 d: Colonies moderately deep, plane; margins entire; mycelium white and primrose (66); texture velvety; sporulation dense; conidia 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="75">en masse</emphasis>
yellow green (71); soluble pigments absent; exudates clear droplets; reverse greyish yellow-green (68). CREA 25 °C, 7 d: No growth.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="75" type="micromorphology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75">Micromorphology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75">
Conidiophores biverticillate, with a minor proportion having subterminal branches; stipes smooth, 70-130 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
3-4 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
, extra branches 10-20 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
; metulae 3-5, divergent, 8.5-11 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
4-4.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
; phialides 4-6, acerose, 9-11 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
3-5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
; conidia smooth, subglobose to fusiform, 2-4.5
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
3-4 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
. Ascomata not observed, white sclerotia present on OA after 1 wk.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="75" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75">
<taxonomicName authorityName="B. D. Sun, A. J. Chen, Houbraken &amp; Samson" authorityYear="2020" class="Eurotiomycetes" family="Aspergillaceae" genus="Talaromyces" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Talaromyces albisclerotius" order="Eurotiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="75" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="albisclerotius">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="75">Talaromyces albisclerotius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is characterized by the production of white sclerotia on OA after 1 wk incubation; these sclerotia remain sterile and no ascospores are observed after prolonged incubation up to eight wk. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Samson &amp; Abdel-Fattah" authorityYear="1978" class="Eurotiomycetes" family="Aspergillaceae" genus="Talaromyces" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Talaromyces assiutensis" order="Eurotiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="75" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="assiutensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="75">Talaromyces assiutensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. trachyspermus" pageId="0" pageNumber="75" rank="species" species="trachyspermus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="75">T. trachyspermus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
could produce white ascomata, but their ascomata mature after weeks and release ascospores (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.simyco.2014.08.001" author="Yilmaz, N" journalOrPublisher="Studies in Mycology" pageId="0" pageNumber="75" pagination="175 - 341" refId="B78" refString="Yilmaz, N, Visagie, CM, Houbraken, J, Frisvad, JC, Samson, RA, 2014. Polyphasic taxonomy of the genus Talaromyces. Studies in Mycology 78: 175 - 341, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.simyco.2014.08.001" title="Polyphasic taxonomy of the genus Talaromyces." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.simyco.2014.08.001" volume="78" year="2014">Yilmaz et al. 2014</bibRefCitation>
). Phylogenetically, 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. albisclerotius" pageId="0" pageNumber="75" rank="species" species="albisclerotius">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="75">T. albisclerotius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
clusters with 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. diversus" pageId="0" pageNumber="75" rank="species" species="diversus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="75">T. diversus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. brasiliensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="75" rank="species" species="brasiliensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="75">T. brasiliensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. diversus" pageId="0" pageNumber="75" rank="species" species="diversus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="75">T. diversus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
grows faster on MEA, and 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. brasiliensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="75" rank="species" species="brasiliensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="75">T. brasiliensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
produces rough conidia (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.simyco.2014.08.001" author="Yilmaz, N" journalOrPublisher="Studies in Mycology" pageId="0" pageNumber="75" pagination="175 - 341" refId="B78" refString="Yilmaz, N, Visagie, CM, Houbraken, J, Frisvad, JC, Samson, RA, 2014. Polyphasic taxonomy of the genus Talaromyces. Studies in Mycology 78: 175 - 341, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.simyco.2014.08.001" title="Polyphasic taxonomy of the genus Talaromyces." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.simyco.2014.08.001" volume="78" year="2014">Yilmaz et al. 2014</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/s10482-018-1081-1" author="Barbosa, RN" journalOrPublisher="Antonie van Leeuwenhoek" pageId="0" pageNumber="75" pagination="1 - 30" refId="B4" refString="Barbosa, RN, Bezerra, JDP, Souza-Motta, CM, Frisvad, JC, Samson, RA, Oliveira, NT, Houbraken, J, 2018. New Penicillium and Talaromyces species from honey, pollen and nests of stingless bees. Antonie van Leeuwenhoek 111: 1 - 30, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1007/s10482-018-1081-1" title="New Penicillium and Talaromyces species from honey, pollen and nests of stingless bees." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/s10482-018-1081-1" volume="111" year="2018">Barbosa et al. 2018</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="75" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75">
Latin, 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="albisclerotius" pageId="0" pageNumber="75" rank="species" species="albisclerotius">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="75">albisclerotius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, refers to its white sclerotia produced on OA.
</paragraph>
